Calculating monthly profit from each user:

In [36]:
def surf_profit (row):
    calls = row['total_min']
    messages = row['total_messages']
    internet = row['total_gb_used']
    
    if calls<= 500:
        cost_calls=0
    else:
        cost_calls=(calls - 500)*0.03
        
    if messages <= 50:
        cost_messages = 0
    else:
        cost_messages = (messages - 50)*0.03
    if internet <= 15:
        cost_internet = 0
    else:
        cost_internet = (internet - 15)*10
    total_profit=cost_calls+cost_messages+cost_internet+20
    return total_profit

def ultimate_profit (row):
    calls = row['total_min']
    messages = row['total_messages']
    internet = row['total_gb_used']
    
    if calls<= 3000:
        cost_calls=0
    else:
        cost_calls=(calls - 3000)*0.01
        
    if messages <= 1000:
        cost_messages = 0
    else:
        cost_messages = (messages - 1000)*0.01
    if internet <= 30:
        cost_internet = 0
    else:
        cost_internet = (internet - 30)*7
    total_profit=cost_calls+cost_messages+cost_internet+70
    return total_profit

Surf plan calls: so, in avarage the users of the surf plan use up to 500 min a month, which is exactly what they have in the package. There are a lot of 0-min but as we assumed earlier these are missed and dropped calls. The data set is skewed a bit to the right meaning there are pretty many users who overuse the free amount of the minutes and pay extra. Those using more than 1000 min a month may be considered the outliers.

sample_1 = data_surf['total_profit']
sample_2 = data_ultimate['total_profit']

alpha = 0.05
                        
results = st.ttest_ind(
        sample_1, 
        sample_2, equal_var = False)

print('p-value: ', results.pvalue)

if (results.pvalue < alpha):
    print("We reject the null hypothesis")
else:
    print("We can't reject the null hypothesis")

p-value:  3.17039054811355e-15
We reject the null hypothesis

The result of this t-test says that there is difference in the avarage profit from the users of the surf and ultimate plan, but we don't have enough info to say how exactly.

Overall conclusion:
I have analyzed two prepaid plans, Surf and Ultimate that the Megaline company offers to its clients. I have studied 3 datasets containing the info about calls, messages, data usage of the clients in 2018. I've rounded up the minutes of calls and mb to gb as the company requires. I've detected many calls with the duration of 0.0 min which I've decided to treat as missed and dropped calls. I have studied in detail the distribution of the usage of min, messages and internet by the clients of the two plans.
The ultimate plan clients do not exceed the prepaid amount of minutes and messages and the majority of them do not exceed the data included in the plan.
The surf plan users do not exceed the number of messages included, they keep close to the minutes limit they have and many pay extra for the internet usage.
The statistical tests that I've conducted show that there is a difference in the monthly avarage profit that two plans bring.
Also the profit from the NY, NJ users is different from the profit from the users from other areas.
It seems that the internet is the most profitable section of the plans - both plans' clients outspend their data limit and pay extra.
